//unebaladeaumerlan.fr/",titre:"Une balade au Merlan",personnes:"Robin de Mourat, Caroline Bougourd, Loup Cellard",citation:" La cité du Merlan à Noisy-le-Sec (Seine-Saint-Denis), chantier expérimental de maisons préfabriquées créé en 1945, est inscrite depuis 2000 en tant que monument historique.\n\nDès lors, comment habiter notre patrimoine ? ",traduction_citation:"",citation_source_nom:"Page d'accueil",citation_source_url:"http://unebaladeaumerlan.fr/",date:"2014",langues:"français",mediums:"vidéo,mécanismes d’interactivité,dessin,musique,disposition spatiale",materiaux:"photographies issues d'un terrain,matériaux issus de terrain,captations vidéo d’entretiens,captations audio d’entretiens,captations vidéos issues d’un terrain,captations audio issues d’un terrain,matériaux issus de fonds d’archives,photographies issues d’archives,enregistrements vidéos issus d’archives,documents numérisés issu d’un terrain","materiaux commentaire":"",perspectives:"histoire, histoire de l'architecture","commentaires perspectives":"",genres:"/",genre_citation:"",genre_source_url:"","traduction genre_citation":"",collections:"",organisations:"",video:"https://vimeo.com/156965630",images:["https://robindemourat.github.io/studiolo/data/4a3232a9-55a5-4b72-91b3-8e50d29253f5.png"],preview:"",cacher:"",plateformes:"",tags:"","répertoires":"",technologies:"",description:"",collection:"pièces"},{id:"unghosting-apparitionnel-lesbian-history","url brute":"http://scalar.usc.edu/works/unghosting-apparitional-lesbians/index",url:"https://web.archive.org/web/20190914235539/https://scalar.usc.edu/works/unghosting-apparitional-lesbians/index","nouvelles urls":"https://web.archive.org/web/20190914235539/https://scalar.usc.edu/works/unghosting-apparitional-lesbians/index",titre:"Unghosting apparitional (lesbian) history -",personnes:"Michelle Moravec",citation:"In Unghosting Apparitional (Lesbian) Histories I explore the internet in search of one woman, the sort of person who doesn’t have papers in a named collection, but who appears scattered throughout resources that also are seldom in one physical location. ",traduction_citation:"",citation_source_nom:"Page d'accueil",citation_source_url:"http://scalar.usc.edu/works/unghosting-apparitional-lesbians/index",date:"2014",langues:"anglais",mediums:"texte",materiaux:"documents numérisés issus d’archives,matériaux issus de fonds d’archives,matériaux relevant de productions culturelles existantes,productions et oeuvres textuelles","materiaux commentaire":"",perspectives:"histoire","commentaires perspectives":"heuristic pondering,                 As I wandered in search of Johnson, I frequently hit dead ends.  The ghosting of Johnson in historical narratives is paralleled by absences in online digitized source material.   In an increasingly digital age, I worry that what gets digitized and put online will be what is more likely to be used in making of new histories.   I have greeted with tempered enthusiasm projects like Reveal Digital's Independent Voices, which contains more than 50,000 pages from the Women's Alternative Press of the 1960s and 1970s.  Online availability of these materials may facilitate histories of women's liberation based on sources beyond the well-known, much-anthologized groups.   However, the online dissemination of digitized materials from an archival collection raises many questions.   As Julie Enzer asked me recently on Twitter, is it right to digitize and make available on the internet the writings of women from decades ago without their consent?   At what point does “public” in the women’s movement become “public” in general?  My project not only raises crucial questions about what gets prioritized in archives for digitization, but also the ethics of online access.  (http://scalar.usc.edu/works/unghosting-apparitional-lesbians/26-conclusion)",genres:"/",genre_citation:"multimodal project using a range of digital tools",genre_source_url:"","traduction genre_citation":"  projet multimodal utilisant une gamme d'outils numériques",collections:"",organisations:"",video:"",images:["https://robindemourat.github.io/studiolo/data/14f422f2-4bac-4bcb-b22b-a812456bec10.png"],preview:"",cacher:"",plateformes:"scalar",tags:"","répertoires":"",technologies:"",description:"",collection:"pièces"},{id:"femtechnet","url brute":"http://scalar.usc.edu/works/ftn-ethnic-studies-pedagogy-workbook-/index",url:"http://scalar.usc.edu/works/ftn-ethnic-studies-pedagogy-workbook-/index","nouvelles urls":"This page was unable to display a Google Maps element. The Google Maps JavaScript API must be downloaded directly from Google's servers. Error Code: NotLoadingAPIFromGoogleMapsError",titre:"Femtechnet",personnes:" Anne Cong-Huyen, Christofer Rodélo, Erica Maria Cheung, Alex Cruse, Regina Yung Lee, KKatie Huang, George Hoagland, Dana Simmons, Sharon Irish, Amanda Phillips, Veronica Paredes, Geneviève Carpio\n \n,",citation:"We keenly feel the pressures of women of color in academia. ",traduction_citation:"",citation_source_nom:"page d'accueil",citation_source_url:"http://scalar.usc.edu/works/ftn-ethnic-studies-pedagogy-workbook-/introduction?path=index",date:"2017",langues:"anglais",mediums:"texte,navigation,vidéo",materiaux:"captations vidéo d’entretiens,documents nativement numériques,matériaux relevant de productions culturelles existantes,productions et oeuvres textuelles","materiaux commentaire":" ",perspectives:"Humanistic studies","commentaires perspectives":"feminist anti MOOC,  FemTechNet DOCC",genres:"workbook",genre_citation:"Acknowledging the challenges of teaching these sensitive and contentious topics in a time of economic retrenchment and increasing institutional precarity for departments of ethnic, gender, and humanisitic studies, this workbook is an ongoing project to build resources for faculty members who are often overburdened at their home institutions, but are willing to take on the difficult task of teaching about gender and racial inequity in our information culture.",genre_source_url:"http://scalar.usc.edu/works/ftn-ethnic-studies-pedagogy-workbook-/introduction?path=index","traduction genre_citation":"document vivant et collaboratif , contributeurs multiples",collections:"",organisations:"",video:"",images:["https://robindemourat.github.io/studiolo/data/c732f9af-915e-4282-b031-40ac5742a4e5.png"],preview:"",cacher:"",plateformes:"scalar",tags:"","répertoires":"",technologies:"",description:"",collection:"pièces"},{id:"a-photographic-history-of-oregon-state-university","url brute":"http://photohistory.oregonstate.edu/works/photo-history/index",url:"http://photohistory.oregonstate.edu/works/photo-history/index","nouvelles urls":"ne s'ouvre pas",titre:"A photographic history of Oregon State University",personnes:"Larry Landis with Osu digital publishing",citation:"This selection of historic photographs of Oregon State University has been developed to introduce you to A School for the People: A Photographic History of Oregon State University (OSU Press, 2015).",traduction_citation:"",citation_source_nom:"page d'accueil",citation_source_url:"http://photohistory.oregonstate.edu/works/photo-history/index",date:"2015",langues:"anglais",mediums:"texte,navigation",materiaux:"matériaux issus de fonds d’archives,photographies issues d’archives","materiaux commentaire":"",perspectives:"histoire ","commentaires perspectives":"",genres:"selection of historic images",genre_citation:'"This selection of historic photographs of Oregon State University has been developed to introduce you to A School for the People: A Photographic History of Oregon State University (OSU Press, 2015).","Please enjoy this selection of historic images of OSU."',genre_source_url:"","traduction genre_citation":"",collections:"",organisations:"",video:"",images:["https://robindemourat.github.io/studiolo/data/cf710c1b-2185-4ea1-a391-e5dd998470fc.png"],preview:"",cacher:"",plateformes:"",tags:"","répertoires":"",technologies:"",description:"",collection:"pièces"},{id:"multimedia-hitchcock","url brute":"https://www.moma.org/interactives/exhibitions/1999/hitchcock/multimedia_kiosk.html",url:"https://www.moma.org/interactives/exhibitions/1999/hitchcock/multimedia_kiosk.html","nouvelles urls":"https://www.moma.org/interactives/exhibitions/1999/hitchcock/multimedia_kiosk.html",titre:"Multimedia Hitchcock",personnes:" Kapsis Dr. Robert E.",citation:"Multimedia Hitchcock is an interactive computer program developed by Dr. Robert E. Kapsis and the Multimedia Hitchcock production team for museums and non-profit film institutions that will be celebrating Alfred Hitchcock's centenary in 1999",traduction_citation:"",citation_source_nom:"page d'accueil",citation_source_url:"https://www.moma.org/interactives/exhibitions/1999/hitchcock/multimedia_kiosk.html",date:"1999",langues:"anglais",mediums:"texte,navigation,disposition spatiale",materiaux:"matériaux issus de fonds d’archives,documents numérisés issus d’archives,enregistrements vidéos issus d’archives,matériaux relevant de productions culturelles existantes,productions et oeuvres textuelles","materiaux commentaire":"",perspectives:"histoire, histoire de l'art","commentaires perspectives":"",genres:"interactive computer program",genre_citation:"Multimedia Hitchcock is an interactive computer program developed by Dr. Robert E. Kapsis and the Multimedia Hitchcock production team for museums and non-profit film institutions that will be celebrating Alfred Hitchcock's centenary in 1999",genre_source_url:"","traduction genre_citation":"",collections:"",organisations:"",video:"",images:["https://robindemourat.github.io/studiolo/data/f9e4af6e-ae66-4a69-a5f7-a06ce99872d1.png"],preview:"",cacher:"",plateformes:"",tags:"","répertoires":"",technologies:"",description:"",collection:"pièces"},{id:"the-death-of the text","url brute":"http://mediacommons.org/intransition/death-text",url:"https://web.archive.org/web/20190224140802/http://mediacommons.org/intransition/death-text","nouvelles urls":"https://web.archive.org/web/20190224140802/http://mediacommons.org/intransition/death-text",titre:"The death of the text",personnes:" Safin David",citation:"To watch the 2015 biopic, Love & Mercy, from the perspective of a discerning authority of the work of Brian Wilson is to revel in the occasion to be a fly on the wall of the recording studio during the production of the landmark album, Pet Sounds. \n\nTo watch it from perspective of a loyal devotee of the life of Brian Wilson is to endure his personal struggles and eventual salvation thanks in part to the efforts of his eventual wife, Melinda Ledbetter. \n\nTo watch it from the perspective of a generalist fan of the sunny heyday of The Beach Boys is to possibly be dissatisfied at the omission of the themes more commonplace in traditional docudramas about musicians.\nAn audience's ability to construe meaning from a biopic is affected by their level of knowledge of the subject, which is dictated by how thoroughly they have engaged texts peripheral to it. Juggling these varied audience expectations is made even more challenging when tackling a subject whose personal narrative is so embedded into the culture. While Brian Wilson may not be a household name, his group, which was given the moniker \"America's Band,\" certainly is. \nn crafting Love & Mercy, director Bill Pohlad weaved a tapestry of allusions, quotations and translations of a vast anthology of media regarding Wilson and The Beach Boys, and as a result placed it among those projects that preceded his own. In doing so, he unconsciously generated a hierarchy among many of those preexistent texts. Constructed utilizing French critic Gerard Genette's theory of \"transtextuality,\" this vidéo aims to illustrate how Pohlad's treatment of many of his sources assigned status to his film's surrounding texts. Those most prominently placed alongside Love & Mercy are the 2000 television mini-series, The Beach Boys: An American Family directed by Jeff Bleckner; The Pet Sounds Sessions Box Set; and the 1995 documentary, Brian Wilson: I Just Wasn't Made for These Times directed by Don Was.\n\nA transtextual reading of Love & Mercy reveals that Pohlad's level of deference was greater for primary sources than for secondary sources. The most interesting relationship exposed via this vidéo lies between Pohlad's and Was' films. Pohlad's adaptation of interviews acquired by Was leave no room for Brian Wilson: I Just Wasn't Made for These Times in the diegesis of Love & Mercy. Therein lies the title of this production, for in Pohlad's interpretation of Wilson, Was' project could not exist.",traduction_citation:"",citation_source_nom:"page d'accueil",citation_source_url:"http://mediacommons.org/intransition/death-text",date:"> 2015",langues:"anglais",mediums:"vidéo,voix parlée",materiaux:"matériaux relevant de productions culturelles existantes,productions et oeuvres audiovisuelles,matériaux issus de fonds d’archives,enregistrements audio issus d’archives,productions et oeuvres textuelles","materiaux commentaire":"",perspectives:"histoire, histoire de l'art","commentaires perspectives":"",genres:"video essay",genre_citation:"The creator declares that his video essay will “demonstrate an unconscious hierarchy” among textual relations crafted by Love and Mercy’s director. This is a modest aim but a worthwhile one. The essay certainly fulfils this and goes beyond it, using Genette’s theories of textual relationships to demonstrate the complexity of this particular films’ (and, by extension, those of other similar docudramas or biopics). I found myself initially hesitant about the value of the Genette framework and what he is being used to say – to me it seems a commonplace that texts might feed on and ultimately eat up previous representations, and the erasure of one film within the fictional diegesis of another can be seen as relatively banal. However, I was ultimately won over by the point the video essay gets to, which reframes the creativity and “innovativeness” of Love and Mercy and employs Barthes’s concepts of authorial “death” in a lucid and genuinely revealing way (where these concepts can be applied in a vague and overly abstract way). Moreover, the arguable “banality” of what Love and Mercy does underlines the broader significance of what Safin is showing us – i.e. it is an understanding that can be applied to other films.\n",genre_source_url:"","traduction genre_citation":"",collections:"",organisations:"media-commons",video:"on Vimeo.",images:["https://robindemourat.github.io/studiolo/data/8c36366f-ca35-4e18-8fcd-12a0a39af441.png"],preview:"",cacher:"",plateformes:"",tags:"","répertoires":"",technologies:"",description:"",collection:"pièces"},{id:"philoweb","url brute":"https://web.archive.org/web/20151001180149/http://www.philoweb.org/",url:"https://web.archive.org/web/20151001180149/http://www.philoweb.org/","nouvelles urls":"https://web.archive.org/web/20151001180149/http://www.philoweb.org/",titre:"Vers une philosophie du web",personnes:" Monin Alexandre",citation:"La création de ce site fut motivée par un constat simple. En dépit des efforts actuels en direction de l’open access, concrétisés par le dépôt électronique des thèses qui offre à chaque docteur la possibilité de publier son travail en ligne (par défaut sur Theses.fr et de manière facultative sur TEL), celui-ci demeure en partie invisible sur le Web compte-tenu du format de publication retenu jusqu’à présent, à savoir le PDF. Aussi, ma thèse prenant pour objet l’architecture du Web, plate-forme ouverte s’il en est, il me semblait logique d’aller plus loin en terme d’accessibilité (et ce, dans tous les sens du terme). C’est pourquoi j’ai décidé de la publier intégralement sur ce site. A cet impératif s’ajoutent les possibilités aujourd’hui offertes par les outils de commentaires en ligne tel CommentPress, ici mis à contribution.",traduction_citation:"Regarder le biopic de 2015, Love & Mercy, du point de vue d'une autorité éclairée de l'œuvre de Brian Wilson, c'est se délecter de l'occasion d'être une mouche sur le mur du studio d'enregistrement pendant la production de l'album historique, Pet Sounds. \r\n\r\nLe voir du point de vue d'un fidèle dévot de la vie de Brian Wilson, c'est endurer ses luttes personnelles et son salut éventuel grâce en partie aux efforts de sa future épouse, Melinda Ledbetter. \r\n\r\nLe voir du point de vue d'un fan généraliste de l'apogée ensoleillée des Beach Boys, c'est ne pas être satisfait de l'omission des thèmes les plus courants dans les docudrames traditionnels sur les musiciens.\r\nLa capacité d'un auditoire à interpréter le sens d'un biopic est influencée  par son niveau de connaissance du sujet, qui est dicté par le degré d'attention qu'il accorde aux textes qui y sont périphériques. Jongler avec ces attentes variées du public est encore plus difficile lorsque l'on aborde un sujet dont le récit personnel est tellement ancré dans la culture. Bien que Brian Wilson ne soit pas un nom familier, son groupe, qui a reçu le surnom de \"America's Band\", l'est certainement. \r\nn créant Love & Mercy, le réalisateur Bill Pohlad a tissé une tapisserie d'allusions, de citations et de traductions d'une vaste anthologie de médias concernant Wilson et The Beach Boys, et l'a ainsi placée parmi les projets qui ont précédé les siens. Ce faisant, il a inconsciemment créé une hiérarchie entre plusieurs de ces textes préexistants. Construite à partir de la théorie de la \"transtextualité\" du critique français Gérard Genette, cette vidéo vise à illustrer comment le traitement par Pohlad d'un grand nombre de ses sources a attribué un statut aux textes environnants de son film. Les plus en vue aux côtés de Love & Mercy sont la mini-série télévisée de 2000, The Beach Boys : An American Family réalisé par Jeff Bleckner ; The Pet Sounds Sessions Box Set ; et le documentaire Brian Wilson : I Just Wasn't Made for These Times réalisé par Don Was en 1995.\r\n\r\nUne lecture transtextuelle de Love & Mercy révèle que le niveau de déférence de Pohlad était plus élevé pour les sources primaires que pour les sources secondaires. La relation la plus intéressante mise en évidence par cette vidéo se situe entre les films de Pohlad et de Was. L'adaptation par Pohlad des interviews acquises par Was ne laisse aucune place à Brian Wilson : I Just Was Was Was Not Was Made for These Times in the diegesis of Love & Mercy. C'est là que se trouve le titre de cette production, car dans l'interprétation de Pohlad de Wilson, le projet Was' ne pouvait exister.",citation_source_nom:"",citation_source_url:"",date:"2011",langues:"français",mediums:"texte",materiaux:"contributions des visiteurs,matériaux relevant de productions culturelles existantes,productions et oeuvres textuelles,productions et oeuvres numériques,documents nativement numériques","materiaux commentaire":"",perspectives:"philosophie","commentaires perspectives":"",genres:"site,publication en HTML",genre_citation:"Bienvenue sur le site consacré à la publication en version HTML de la thèse d’Alexandre Monnin, intitulée Vers une philosophie du Web.",genre_source_url:"","traduction genre_citation":"",collections:"",organisations:"",video:"",images:["https://robindemourat.github.io/studiolo/data/b70b1c59-5815-4b72-ae67-06bdbfcf5158.png"],preview:"",cacher:"",plateformes:"",tags:"","répertoires":"",technologies:"",description:"",collection:"pièces"},{id:"design-et-humanites-numeriques","url brute":"http://esthetique-des-donnees.editions-b42.com/#index",url:"https://web.archive.org/web/20191022181202/http://esthetique-des-donnees.editions-b42.com/#index","nouvelles urls":"https://web.archive.org/web/20191022181202/http://esthetique-des-donnees.editions-b42.com/#index",titre:"Design et humanités numériques",personnes:" Masure Anthony",citation:"En étudiant des opérations et des systèmes techniques potentiellement ouverts à la recherche, cet essai interroge le rapport du design aux « humanités numériques » (digital humanities) qui se développent, dans le contexte francophone, depuis le milieu des années 2000. En quoi les environnements numériques contemporains actualisent-ils les modes de production et de transmission des savoirs ? Quelle est la place des designers dans des projets relevant des sciences humaines et sociales ? De la modélisation des connaissances à l’injonction à l’innovation et à la créativité, du design d’expérience aux conditionnements techniques, de l’étude de la rationalité numérique aux reconfigurations de la subjectivité, ce parcours réflexif montre que l’industrie des programmes, chaque jour un peu plus puissante, n’a pas épuisé tout le champ des possibles. En interrogeant et en révélant l’environnement technique dans lequel les humanités numériques opèrent, le travail des techniques numériques par le design montre ainsi qu’il reste de la place pour d’autres modulations, d’autres sensibilités, d’autres cultures. ",traduction_citation:"",citation_source_nom:"",citation_source_url:"",date:"2017",langues:"français",mediums:"texte,disposition spatiale,navigation",materiaux:"matériaux relevant de productions culturelles existantes,productions et oeuvres textuelles,productions et oeuvres visuelles,matériaux issus d’une publication imprimée antérieure","materiaux commentaire":"",perspectives:"design,humanités numériques","commentaires perspectives":"",genres:"contenu complémentaire",genre_citation:"",genre_source_url:"","traduction genre_citation":"",collections:"",organisations:"",video:"",images:["https://robindemourat.github.io/studiolo/data/c8e29ff1-b047-45b9-b095-6d161dc7e85f.png"],preview:"",cacher:"",plateformes:"",tags:"","répertoires":"",technologies:"",description:"",collection:"pièces"}]}},function(e,t,i){"use strict";function n(e,t){var i={};for(var n in e)t.indexOf(n)>=0||Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call(e,n)&&(i[n]=e[n]);return i}Object.defineProperty(t,"__esModule",{value:!0});var a=Object.assign||function(e){for(var t=1;t<argume